00:09.020 --> 00:13.140
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:30.000 --> 00:35.400
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:38.260 --> 00:39.920
And here are your hosts.

00:44.020 --> 00:46.320
This is Bill Vernon and David Carson.

00:46.580 --> 00:52.620
Edward Bryant is on the forefront of the young writers who will likely shape the course of science fiction in the 80s and 90s.

00:52.760 --> 00:55.080
We asked Bryant his definition of science fiction.

00:56.240 --> 00:59.280
Science fiction is essentially the same as any other fiction.

00:59.480 --> 01:05.120
It's fiction about people, about characters, about the relationships between one character and another,

01:05.160 --> 01:08.340
or one character and a group, which may be society,

01:08.600 --> 01:17.460
with the difference from mainstream fiction being that in science fiction there is some sort of scientific or technological development

01:17.460 --> 01:23.360
which is important to the story and which affects those human relationships

01:23.360 --> 01:29.500
between person and other person or person and people as a group.

01:30.600 --> 01:32.660
Bryant grew up on a ranch in Wyoming.

01:32.960 --> 01:36.460
After he completed graduate school, he began writing short stories.

01:36.920 --> 01:39.440
To date, he has published three collections of short stories,

01:39.820 --> 01:42.900
"Among the Dead", "Cinnabar", and "Particle Theory".

01:43.140 --> 01:46.260
We asked Bryant why he prefers to work in the medium of the short story.

01:46.920 --> 01:49.200
It's not a matter of conscious choice.

01:49.520 --> 01:53.120
I write what I do because that is what I do.

01:55.160 --> 01:57.360
I plan to write novels.

01:57.720 --> 02:00.280
Of course, I've been planning to write novels for a long time.

02:00.760 --> 02:08.940
My publisher is expecting by October 1st a novel which was originally contracted in 1974,

02:09.800 --> 02:14.220
and this is a long while to be dithering about completing the book.

02:17.960 --> 02:26.240
Short stories have just always seemed to me the appropriate medium that I should work in.

02:27.320 --> 02:29.720
In some ways, I could agree.

02:30.000 --> 02:35.100
I feel like short stories are mini novels

02:36.080 --> 02:43.600
because I have often spent much more time in terms of working out the characterizations,

02:43.600 --> 02:45.960
the plots, and so forth and so on,

02:46.840 --> 02:52.900
than the amount of space in that short story would indicate.

02:54.720 --> 03:03.440
There are stories of mine that seem to me to be almost compressed novels that, under other circumstances,

03:03.720 --> 03:08.880
were I more prolific writer, I probably could have expanded them out another 54,000 words

03:08.880 --> 03:13.980
and got a nice paperback original novel.

03:14.660 --> 03:19.320
But I like to work with the compression sometimes.

03:19.320 --> 03:21.960
I like to pack an incredible amount,

03:22.200 --> 03:23.840
which is a risk, of course,

03:23.840 --> 03:32.480
because I fully recognize that a lot of people who read my stuff

03:32.480 --> 03:36.460
don't care to deal in that sort of thing.

03:36.740 --> 03:39.920
They don't want to have to worry about putting that kind of energy

03:39.920 --> 03:43.500
into reading a short story that they might ordinarily apply

03:43.500 --> 03:46.820
to at least starting to approach a novel.

03:48.060 --> 03:51.380
Phoenix Without Ashes is Bryant's only novel published to date,

03:51.520 --> 03:53.760
and it's a collaboration with Harlan Ellison.

03:54.020 --> 03:56.900
We ask if he is planning to publish a novel eventually.

03:57.800 --> 04:00.740
I think, I really believe,

04:01.040 --> 04:03.320
that there are things that I want to write about

04:03.320 --> 04:08.400
that I can treat much better as novels,

04:08.440 --> 04:09.780
but I can't as short stories.

04:10.040 --> 04:11.840
And I think I would do that.

04:12.080 --> 04:15.080
I think right now the bottleneck factor

04:15.080 --> 04:20.360
is that I haven't done a scratch novel that's worked.

04:20.880 --> 04:23.220
I've done Phoenix, which is a novelization.

04:23.220 --> 04:26.960
I've done Cinnabar, which is a sort of piecework novel

04:26.960 --> 04:31.080
made up of parts that were originally published as short stories.

04:31.500 --> 04:34.900
And I've done a 60,000-word novel,

04:34.900 --> 04:38.540
which remains in my files, has never been rewritten,

04:38.700 --> 04:40.280
has never been submitted professionally,

04:40.520 --> 04:42.160
is not science fiction or fantasy.

04:42.300 --> 04:44.860
It's the traditional college novel

04:44.860 --> 04:47.420
that editors know and abominate.

04:47.600 --> 04:50.020
They get thousands of them every year.

04:50.200 --> 04:52.940
They're the novels that people write just after college,

04:52.940 --> 04:55.920
in which the young writer says,

04:56.100 --> 04:58.520
well, I have come of age in this society,

04:58.520 --> 05:01.500
and here are the wonderful truths that I have learned.

05:01.780 --> 05:03.440
And they put all this into fiction,

05:03.440 --> 05:06.520
and it's usually just pretty terrible stuff.

05:07.260 --> 05:09.240
More on Edward Bryant on our next show.

