so stay with us.

18:16.780 --> 18:19.300
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show,

18:19.520 --> 18:22.160
a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

18:24.920 --> 18:26.580
And here are your hosts.

18:31.180 --> 18:32.540
This is David Carson.

18:32.780 --> 18:33.480
And Bill Vernon.

18:33.820 --> 18:37.300
Today we continue with our interview with science fiction author Edward Bryant.

18:37.680 --> 18:40.200
Those who are at all familiar with Bryant's work

18:40.200 --> 18:43.160
have certainly come across his apparent fascination with sharks.

18:43.160 --> 18:46.200
Here he explains how this attraction was spawned,

18:46.220 --> 18:49.160
then how it led to the famous short story titled simply,

18:49.620 --> 18:49.800
Shark.

18:50.800 --> 18:51.920
Why sharks?

18:53.840 --> 18:55.660
You know, when people visit my apartment,

18:55.660 --> 18:57.280
they see all sorts of shark paraphernalia,

18:58.000 --> 19:00.160
you know, jaws mounted on backboards

19:00.160 --> 19:03.900
and shark mobiles, shark paintings,

19:04.080 --> 19:05.020
and so forth and so on.

19:06.020 --> 19:08.700
The reason for the shark motif,

19:09.560 --> 19:14.200
and the reason that I suppose I've adopted the shark as a sort of totem,

19:14.560 --> 19:17.000
is because in the early 70s,

19:17.630 --> 19:21.500
one of my closest friends had dreamed the night before,

19:21.720 --> 19:23.300
and she told me about this at breakfast,

19:23.300 --> 19:26.360
that she had been in the body of a shark.

19:26.680 --> 19:31.100
She had seen the world through shark-colored lenses.

19:33.280 --> 19:35.560
And we talked about this for a while,

19:35.740 --> 19:38.780
you know, got past the obvious Freudian symbolism of it all,

19:39.980 --> 19:41.900
and I was fascinated by the dream.

19:43.380 --> 19:45.800
Then she catalyzed action by saying,

19:45.920 --> 19:49.680
listen, why don't you write a story about sharks?

19:49.960 --> 19:51.700
Now, I didn't know anything about sharks.

19:51.700 --> 19:54.840
I was just an inland boy who'd grown up far from the sea,

19:54.860 --> 19:57.500
and although the ocean has always fascinated me,

19:57.600 --> 19:58.580
I didn't know about sharks.

19:58.760 --> 20:02.000
But I did my research, just as with, say, "Particle Theory".

20:02.000 --> 20:03.680
I found out about sharks.

20:03.800 --> 20:06.340
I became intrigued by their position

20:06.340 --> 20:08.640
in the evolutionary scheme of things,

20:08.720 --> 20:11.120
how incredibly well-developed they are.

20:11.380 --> 20:14.640
And I was also struck by such images

20:14.640 --> 20:16.800
as the fact that the shark

20:16.800 --> 20:19.860
is the major species of creature

20:19.860 --> 20:22.500
which is hostile to human beings,

20:22.500 --> 20:26.480
which is in no danger of extinction, at least at this point.

20:27.300 --> 20:31.740
So I took my friend's original dream

20:31.740 --> 20:37.300
and I said, okay, I've got a character who wants to be a shark.

20:37.620 --> 20:39.660
Why does she want to be a shark?

20:39.880 --> 20:44.000
How does she become a shark, both metaphorically and literally?

20:44.360 --> 20:47.800
And that's how the original shark story generated.

20:48.980 --> 20:51.340
I realized after finishing the story

20:51.340 --> 20:54.280
that there were other things that involved sharks

20:54.280 --> 20:56.420
that I had not dealt with in the story

20:56.420 --> 21:00.420
that I would treat in various other pieces.

21:08.620 --> 21:13.960
When Bryant's friends got wind of his newfound fascination, he began to be bombarded with shark mementos.

21:14.700 --> 21:21.640
What happened then, of course, was the older you get, I think the harder you are to shop for your friends and relatives.

21:21.940 --> 21:23.160
They don't know what to get you.

21:23.360 --> 21:24.780
They don't know what your tastes are.

21:24.880 --> 21:27.860
They don't know what books you've read or what albums you don't have.

21:29.940 --> 21:36.060
So somehow the shark story caught the fancy of the people around me and I started giving me shark paraphernalia.

21:36.160 --> 21:39.200
Before I knew it, I had more sharks than I knew what to do with.

21:39.960 --> 21:48.380
I'm glad it was sharks because Jaws notwithstanding, there never has been that much in the way of shark artifacts for sale.

21:48.540 --> 21:56.460
If it had been unicorns or dragons, say I would have been swamped completely and utterly and I could have knick-knack and gee-gaw garage sales.

21:57.340 --> 22:00.020
But instead, I've got some pretty neat shark stuff.

22:00.380 --> 22:02.460
Does Bryant really like sharks?

22:03.300 --> 22:08.480
I would say, though, that people ask me, do I really like sharks?

22:08.620 --> 22:13.600
And I have to admit, I don't like sharks. Nobody likes sharks, but I respect sharks.

22:14.340 --> 22:20.640
And sharks as an emblem, as a symbol, truly do fascinate me.

22:20.860 --> 22:23.400
And I expect there will be other Shark stories.

22:23.720 --> 22:25.560
There may even be a Shark novel.

22:25.740 --> 22:40.560
What militates against a shark novel, of course, quite aside from any of my own feelings about writing a novel, is I probably have to wait for the furore of Peter Benchley's Jaws to continue dying down.

22:41.840 --> 22:43.840
More on Edward Bryant on our next show.

