And here are your hosts.

24:14.900 --> 24:16.180
This is David Carson.

24:16.200 --> 24:16.920
And Bill Vernon.

24:17.160 --> 24:22.040
In the fall of 1981, Edward Bryant's important short story collection, Particle Theory, was published.

24:22.320 --> 24:32.380
It contains memorable stories, "The Thermals of August", the Nebula Award-winning "giANTS", the often reprinted "Shark", "The Hibakusha Gallery", and the title story.

24:32.580 --> 24:38.860
The story "Particle Theory" is unique in Bryant's canon in that its background is heavily laden with hard science.

24:38.860 --> 24:44.680
Here he explains how any writer can get across hard science ideas if he uses the right resources.

24:45.600 --> 24:56.740
"Particle Theory" came about because I read a newspaper article about pion beam therapy using a stream of solid particles, subnuclear particles, to attack cancerous tumors,

24:57.380 --> 25:02.700
which I have just found out is a line of research that has just been abandoned down at Los Alamos.

25:02.700 --> 25:09.640
I'm not sure why, whether it's funding cutbacks or whether they've simply found better means to attack the medical problem.

25:09.800 --> 25:16.960
But at any rate, what had intrigued me a number of years ago in the paper is now apparently scientifically dead.

25:18.160 --> 25:29.020
And yeah, this is more of a hard science story than I customarily write, but I think it exhibits a more general principle,

25:29.280 --> 25:44.060
which is that I or every other writer who may not be all that soundly based in science and technology by discipline or by vocation need simply only use the research tools

25:44.060 --> 25:52.900
that we all presumably learned in junior high to get across a hard science story without being overly didactic about it.

25:53.140 --> 26:00.140
What I discovered in this story was that the world is full of experts who were quite willing to share with me their specialized knowledge,

26:00.140 --> 26:09.920
whether it was particle beam physics or whether it was the landscape around Los Alamos and little details for verisimilitude,

26:09.920 --> 26:16.600
such as what airline do you fly into Los Alamos on and what sort of planes are you in and all of that kind of thing.

26:17.220 --> 26:22.420
Bryant comments here on the fact that he does not wish to be typecast as a writer of any particular type of story.

26:23.260 --> 26:26.980
True. Ordinarily, I don't use quite so much scientific content.

26:27.460 --> 26:41.920
All I can say is this was one of the stories in which that content seemed appropriate and it exhibits my own, in a sense, my own sense of frustration with being typecast.

26:42.620 --> 26:59.880
I write what I like to write and sometimes that may be a story which is full of medical research about prostate cancer and particle beam therapy for that cancer and cosmology, all that.

27:00.680 --> 27:08.280
And other times I will write science fiction stories in which there is not a speck of hard research or hard fact.

27:09.240 --> 27:14.440
Again, I suppose it illustrates the difference between facts and truths to be facile about it.

27:16.180 --> 27:20.420
But it also shows that good research can cover a multitude of sins.

27:20.760 --> 27:26.160
He maintains that even with the hard science elements, "Particle Theory" is still a people story.

27:26.640 --> 27:29.640
This story for me is still a people story first and foremost.

27:30.300 --> 27:40.380
It's, again, about relationships of people and the scientific content amplifies, illustrates, and I hope clarifies those relationships.

27:40.760 --> 27:45.800
But, by God, the people still come first and the science and technology come second.

27:51.820 --> 27:56.180
Bryant's first published short story collection, Among the Dead, came out in 1973.

27:56.560 --> 27:59.480
It contains a number of stories written early in his career.

27:59.760 --> 28:10.200
His novel, Phoenix Without Ashes, is in fact a novelization of Harlan Ellison's original pilot script for the ill-fated television series, The Star Lost. This work is a rarity.

28:10.400 --> 28:17.740
As a novelization, which came after the fact, it is actually a solid piece of work. The planned sequels have never materialized.

28:18.040 --> 28:24.460
Certainly, Edward Bryant has established himself as a top-flight writer who happens also to work under the label science fiction.

